Suspicious Links (URLs)
‚úÖ 1. Hover Before You Click
        a. Action: Hover your mouse over the link (don‚Äôt click!).

        b. Check: The actual URL will show in the bottom-left of your browser or email client.

        c. Red Flags:

        d. Misspelled domains (e.g., micr0soft.com instead of microsoft.com)

        e. IP addresses instead of domain names (e.g., http://192.168.1.2/login)

        f. Suspicious domain endings (e.g., .xyz, .top, .click, .tk)

        g. Subdomains tricking you (e.g., paypal.com.scammer-site.com)

üö© 2. Look for Obfuscation
        a. Hidden in buttons, shortened URLs (bit.ly, tinyurl, etc.), or encoded (e.g., %68%74%74%70).

        b. These can mask the real destination.

            Tip: Use link expanders:

            https://www.expandurl.net/
            https://checkshorturl.com/


# Common Dangerous File Types
File Type	                          Risk

.exe, .bat, .scr, .cmd	          Executable malware
.js	                              Script-based malware
.doc, .xls, .ppt with macros	    Malicious macro viruses
.zip, .rar	                      Compressed malware or ransomware
.pdf	                            Can contain scripts or phishing links


# Examples of Unsafe Links

1. Spoofed Domain
hxxps://microsoft-support-login[.]com
‚úÖ Looks official, but it's not Microsoft's domain.
‚ùå Microsoft uses *.microsoft.com, not this fake domain.

2. Lookalike Characters
hxxps://www.paypaI.com/login
Uses an uppercase "I" (paypaI) instead of lowercase "l" (paypal).
Visually identical, but leads to a malicious site.

3. IP Address-Based Link
hxxp://198.51.100.23/bank-login
No domain name at all ‚Äî uses a raw IP.
Often used in malware distribution or fake login pages.

